[[File:Batman villains 1966.jpg|thumb|Supervillains from the 1966 film ''[[Batman (1966 film)|Batman]]'', a film adaptation of the comic books based on [[Batman]] and the 1960s [[Batman (TV series)|television show]] of the same name. From left to right: [[Penguin (comics)|Penguin]], [[Riddler]], [[Catwoman]], and [[Joker (character)|Joker]].]]
A '''supervillain''' is a variant of the [[villain]]ous [[stock character]] that is commonly found in [[American comic book]]s, usually possessing [[superhuman]] abilities. A supervillain is the antithesis of a [[superhero]]. A female supervillain is sometimes called a '''supervillainess'''{{citation-needed|date=August 2018}}, although the word supervillain is commonly used for females also.

Supervillains are often used as [[foil (literature)|foils]] to present a daunting challenge to a superhero. In instances where the supervillain does not have superhuman, mystical, or alien powers, the supervillain may possess a genius intellect or a skill set that allows them to draft complex schemes or commit crimes in a way normal humans cannot. Other traits may include [[megalomania]] and possession of considerable resources to further their aims. Many supervillains share some typical characteristics of real world [[dictator]]s, [[gangster]]s, and [[terrorism|terrorists]], with aspirations of [[world domination]] or universal leadership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comicon.com/cgi-bin/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_topic;f=36;t=006131;p=0 |title=Eury & Misiroglu On The Supervillain Book |publisher=Comicon.Com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218045716/http://www.comicon.com/cgi-bin/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_topic;f=36;t=006131;p=0 |archivedate=2012-02-18 |df= }}</ref>

==Notable supervillains==
The [[Joker (character)|Joker]], [[Lex Luthor]], [[Magneto (comics)|Magneto]], [[Doctor Doom]], [[Darkseid]], [[Venom (Marvel Comics character)|Venom]], [[Ra's al Ghul]], and [[Thanos]] are some notable male comic book supervillains and have been [[Film adaptation|adapted]] to film and television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2008/06/18/the-joker-tops-supervillain-poll-199239/ |title=Joker tops supervillain poll |publisher=Metro.co.uk |date=2012-04-25 |accessdate=2012-05-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicbooks.about.com/od/characters/tp/toptenvillains.htm |title=Top Ten Comic Book Super Villains |publisher=Comicbooks.about.com |date=2012-04-10 |accessdate=2012-05-09}}</ref> Some notable examples of female supervillains are the [[Catwoman]], [[Mystique (comics)|Mystique]], [[Harley Quinn]], [[Talia al Ghul]], [[Poison Ivy (comics)|Poison Ivy]], [[Hela (comics)|Hela]] and [[Phoenix Force (comics)|Dark Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/15629-lethal-ladies-the-10-best-female-supervillains.html|title=Lethal Ladies ; The 10 Best Female Supervillains|publisher=Newsarama.com|accessdate=2013-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/2801704/maleficent-villains-wicked-witch-catwoman/|title=Maleficent and 16 Other Famous Queens of Mean|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=2015-04-09}}</ref>

Just like superheroes, supervillains are sometimes members of supervillain groups, such as the [[Sinister Six]], the [[Suicide Squad]], the [[Brotherhood of Mutants]], the [[Injustice League]], the [[Legion of Doom]], and the [[Masters of Evil]].

